# --- Python / build --------------------------------------------------------
__pycache__/
*.py[cod]
.pytest_cache/
.ruff_cache/
*.egg-info/
build/
dist/
.venv/
venv/
.DS_Store

# --- transient test / review artifacts -------------------------------------
*junit*.xml

# --- generated figures -----------------------------------------------------
# Build output, not source.  Rebuild with:  python examples/demo.py --figures
/figures/

# --- agent + editor tooling artifacts --------------------------------------
# Claude Code config, subagent workflow scripts, scratch notes.  These describe
# how the work was done on one machine; they are not part of the library.
/.claude/

# AGENTS.md is the Codex-facing sibling of CLAUDE.md -- agent guidance, not a
# project document.  CLAUDE.md is tracked only because the README and this repo's
# own conventions lean on it; AGENTS.md duplicates it for a second tool and would
# drift.  Keep it on disk, out of git.  (It is still listed in .gitattributes, so
# the obsidian-strip filter applies if it is ever tracked deliberately.)
/AGENTS.md

# --- working documents: planning, research, handoffs -----------------------
# POLICY.  This repository tracks only the standard project documents at the
# root -- README.md, CLAUDE.md, CONTRIBUTING.md, SECURITY.md, LICENSE -- plus
# the documents the README links to directly, which live under docs/ and are
# un-ignored one by one below.
#
# Everything else under docs/ is a working artifact: ROADMAP, GOALS, HANDOFF,
# literature surveys, gap analyses, revamp prompts, and any agent-generated
# planning note.  They stay on disk (and in the Obsidian vault); they do not go
# into git.  The pre-commit hook in .githooks/ enforces this -- see
# CONTRIBUTING.md.
#
# Adding a doc here is a deliberate act: un-ignore it ONLY if the README links
# to it, and add it to ALLOWED_DOCS in .githooks/pre-commit at the same time.
/docs/*
!/docs/CORRECTIONS.md
